84–1430":"1384–1430","1319–Male":"1319–Afdød","1308–1346":"1308–1346","1338":"1338","1346":"1346","1354":"1354","1430":"1430","1330":"1330","1384":"1384","Abt 1346":"omkring 1346","1308":"1308","1319":"1319","Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Bradfield, Tiverton, Essex, England":"Bradfield, Essex, England"},"nl":{"Abt 1346–":"circa 1346–Overleden","1330–Male":"1330–Overleden","1338–Female":"1338–Overleden","1346–Male":"1346–Overleden","1354–Female":"1354–Overleden","1384–1430":"1384–1430","1319–Male":"1319–Overleden","1308–1346":"1308–1346","1338":"1338","1346":"1346","1354":"1354","1430":"1430","1330":"1330","1384":"1384","Abt 1346":"circa 1346","1308":"1308","1319":"1319","Devon, England":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bradfield, Tiverton, Essex, England":"Bradfield, Essex, England"},"en":{"Abt 1346–":"about 1346–Deceased","1330–Male":"1330–Deceased","1338–Female":"1338–Deceased","1346–Male":"1346–Deceased","1354–Female":"1354–Deceased","1384–1430":"1384–1430","1319–Male":"1319–Deceased","1308–1346":"1308–1346","1338":"1338","1346":"1346","1354":"1354","1430":"1430","1330":"1330","1384":"1384","Abt 1346":"about 1346","1308":"1308","1319":"1319","Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Bradfield, Tiverton, Essex, England":"Bradfield, Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Walrond","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Somerset and Devon): of Normin origin, a variant of   Waldron  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Worland","meanings":["English (Cambridge): of Norman origin, possibly a metathesised variant of   Walrond   (see   Waldron  )."]},{"name":"Waldron","meanings":["English and Irish (Mayo): from the Norman personal name <i>Waleran</i>, <i>Galeran</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Walahram</i>, Old French <i>Galeran(t)</i>), composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>walh</i> ‘foreigner’ + <i>hrafn</i> ‘raven’. Compare   Walraven  . In Ireland, where it is common, this name was Gaelicized early as <b>Mac Bhalronta</b>, also later as <b>Mac Bhaildrin</b> and <b>de Bhaldraithe</b>.","English: habitational name from a place in Sussex named Waldron. The placename derives from Old English <i>wald</i> ‘woodland’ + <i>ærn</i> ‘building’.","History: This is the name of a prominent NH family, established there since the 17th century. Richard Walderne (born <i>c.</i> 1615) came to New England from Alchester, Warwickshire, England, <i>c.</i> 1640 and settled at Dover, NH."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When John II Walrond was born about 1346, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Walrond of Bradfield, was 29 and his mother, Joan Stowford, was 40. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. John II Walrond."},"et":{"Abt 1346–":"umbes 1346–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1338–Female":"1338–Surnud","1346–Male":"1346–Surnud","1354–Female":"1354–Surnud","1384–1430":"1384–1430","1319–Male":"1319–Surnud","1308–1346":"1308–1346","1338":"1338","1346":"1346","1354":"1354","1430":"1430","1330":"1330","1384":"1384","Abt 1346":"umbes 1346","1308":"1308","1319":"1319","Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bradfield, Tiverton, Essex, England":"Bradfield, Essex, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1346–":"noin 1346–Kuollut","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1338–Female":"1338–Kuollut","1346–Male":"1346–Kuollut","1354–Female":"1354–Kuollut","1384–1430":"1384–1430","1319–Male":"1319–Kuollut","1308–1346":"1308–1346","1338":"1338","1346":"1346","1354":"1354","1430":"1430","1330":"1330","1384":"1384","Abt 1346":"noin 1346","1308":"1308","1319":"1319","Devon, England":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bradfield, Tiverton, Essex, England":"Bradfield, Essex, England"},"fr":{"Abt 1346–":"environ 1346–Décédé","1330–Male":"1330–Décédé","1338–Female":"1338–Décédée","1346–Male":"1346–Décédé","1354–Female":"1354–Décédée","1384–1430":"1384–1430","1319–Male":"1319–Décédé","1308–1346":"1308–1346","1338":"1338","1346":"1346","1354":"1354","1430":"1430","1330":"1330","1384":"1384","Abt 1346":"environ 1346","1308":"1308","1319":"1319","Devon, England":"Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Bradfield, Tiverton, Essex, England":"Bradfield, Essex, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque John II Walrond est né environ 1346, à Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, John Walrond of Bradfield, avait 29 ans et sa mère, J